[
  {
    "id": "intro",
    "text": "Momentum in Stochastic Gradient Descent. Let's visualize how velocity accumulates as a ball rolls down a curved loss landscape.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  },
  {
    "id": "landscape",
    "text": "Here we see the loss landscape. The curve represents how the loss changes with different parameter values. Our goal is to find the minimum.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  },
  {
    "id": "gradient",
    "text": "The gradient points in the direction of steepest ascent. We follow the negative gradient to minimize the loss.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  },
  {
    "id": "momentum",
    "text": "With momentum, we accumulate velocity over time. The ball picks up speed as it rolls and carries momentum through the valley.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  },
  {
    "id": "overshoot",
    "text": "Notice how the ball overshoots the minimum and oscillates, gradually settling due to the momentum coefficient damping.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  },
  {
    "id": "conclusion",
    "text": "Momentum helps accelerate convergence and can help escape local minima. The accumulated velocity carries us faster toward the optimum.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 0.95
  }
]
